spanGrp.span: Hegu hagoreiza hikukuk haniharegi naapak hogihira (ho)watekjanawi.
Once when I was young we went to pick cherries.
hegu haagoriza hiikukk hanihregi naapk hogihra wawatkjanawi
Heesge naan eera naan eerasana (nigiap) no niipnaksana eegi heesge eeja (ho)wataawi.
My mother, still living, said we would go there.
heske naanera naanerasana niki'ap no ni'pnaksana egi heske 'eeja wtaawi
nigi'ap = one of yours is living
Hira(w)ahasrasge cuusgni nunge waak (waak) waza_hoki waaniniiza zee hiira hicito haara hiza hirawahas gigi anaga ee howataawi.
We had no driver, one of our male relatives, one of our older brothers, we got him to drive.
hir(w)ahas aske cusgni nunge waak waak wazki waniniza ze'e hra hicithara hiza hirawhas gig anaga e howatwi
ze'e hii-ra = waza hii-ra 'the ones s/he is related to'
<<fs>Green> Green Bay sikeja hahi eeja eeja Haramehi_haap nuupahaxji niisge eeja hahi hauwiguni or taaniha.
Past Green Bay we went for two or three Sundays.
Green Bay sigeja hahi 'eeja 'eeja harumhe haap nupahaxji nisk 'eeja hahi h'uwiguni or taaniha

Hinigi xapgek hakika(w)auwi anaga hegu maixeteiza maanka ee hani
We got up early in the morning, this white man who owned the land,
hanegi xap gg hakik(w)a'uwi anaga hegu maxeteiza maanka e hani
naapak hozu zeesge eeja peehi waauwina.
there we picked cherries (with a cherry bucket).
Hinigi hinixjik hija hau reex hirarutiiza ruti hii anaga eeja reexra jagu gallon pail reexiza heesge hanac hizasana tuuswi anaga.
Early in the morning the wagon would come by and each of us would all take one of those pails.
haegi hanexjig hiju'u reex hirartiiza rut hianaga 'eeja rexra jagu gallon pail rexiza heske hanac hiasana tzwi anaga
ee hoixji hoixji wahaawregi zige hiraruti hacija reexra watuswigi eeja haakja hani hagiwi waakjeega hija wagaxsunu.
When we filled them, we would take the pails back to the wagon that brought them and that man used to write it down.
zee hixji hixji waha(w)negi zig hirarti hacja rexra watzwigi 'eeja hakja hanigi waak jega hijwagaxsunu
Jaanga peehi raas hija (h)gitup jaanga peehi hija wagaxsunu.
He put our name down and how many we picked he used to write down.
janga phi raazhij(ah)git'up janga phi hijwagaxsunu
eegu haawi anaga hakiijire waauwi hegu.
zegu ha anaga hakijre wa'uwi hegu

Today those things they are able to can or freeze them and that's the way we buy them, it wasn't that way.
ze'e hpte'e gnige waza heske wazakasge maskokeja woz anaga nigske jasg hiyaruwi 'anaga ke heskni

eegu zuura kiiku nai wauajawi heesge (he)gu hakipanu hauwisunu.

zgu zur kik'u na'i w'uajawi hskegu hakipna h'uwisunu
One time I fell out of a tree.

They were all over the ground and I couldn't pick them all.
hanac maja spre ke peh tuxrukni
Naati hawi anaga zeesge peehi waauwisunu.
We used to climb the trees and pick them.
naat ha'wi anaga zske phi wa'uwisunu
Hegu anaga eegi waakisipwira kuukjana(w)ira wareika naan eera zuura hiruwe gigi jaanaga reexra peehi hija uaniha(w)i.
And then when we were finished and we were going to come back the white man payed my mother the money for all that we picked.
hegu anaga egi waksipwira kuksana(w)ra wareka naanera zur hirawagigi janga rxra phi hija'uniha(w)i
Eeja anaga hige eeja guuwi eegi tookregi waauaja(w)i hahi eeja caaniregi hige hauwi naani eera hakaraikizu hau.
And then we came back, it was the summer time, and then in the fall I did it (again) along with my mother.
ejanaga higeeja guwi egi tokrgi wa'uaj(w)i haheja caninegi hig ha'uwi naaiera hakaraik hi'uwi

Hicak haara hakaraikizu naan eera, eegi hoocke peehiwi hacija wiigihiura rusj anaga.
my younger sister and my mother, we would pick cranberries, wherever they finished raking.
hicakhara karak hi'uwi naanera egi hocke pehwi hacja wighi'una rusjanaga
Eeja zee hoocke hoocke hirukna haip eeja hisge hapehi anaga,
There the cranberry boss, if we like to pick there,
'eeja ze hocke hirukna haip eeja hiske haphi anaga
We used to pick all the fallen ones.
Hegu bushel box heesge heesge eeja waazuwisunu.

hegu busel box heske heskeja wazuwisunu

And then in the evening when we were finished if we filled a box we didn't carry the boxes, we left them there, in the evening the whiteman would come by and pick them up and they were paying us.
